<p><a name="Popular_culture" id="Popular_culture"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=The_Man_Who_Was_Thursday&amp;action=edit&amp;section=14" title="Edit section: Popular culture">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Popular culture</span></h2>
<ul>
<li>In the popular video game <i><a href="/wiki/Deus_Ex" title="Deus Ex">Deus Ex</a></i>, one can read excerpts from the novel in books located in several areas of the game. Also in the game is a narcotic called "Zyme". Gabriel Syme is also listed as a guest at a hotel in the game.</li>
<li><a href="/wiki/Robert_Hanssen" title="Robert Hanssen">Robert Hanssen</a>, the staunchly Catholic FBI agent who was arrested and convicted in 2001 for selling state secrets to the USSR and, later, the Russian Federation, was a great admirer of this book. He used to recommend it and lend copies of the book to friends and co-workers. See the book by Vise, <i><a href="/w/index.php?title=The_Bureau_and_the_Mole&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="The Bureau and the Mole (page does not exist)">The Bureau and the Mole</a></i>.</li>
<li>Syme (no first name given) is a co-worker and frequent lunch companion of <a href="/wiki/Winston_Smith" title="Winston Smith">Winston Smith</a> at the Ministry of Truth in <a href="/wiki/George_Orwell" title="George Orwell">George Orwell</a>'s novel <i><a href="/wiki/Nineteen_Eighty-four" title="Nineteen Eighty-four" class="mw-redirect">Nineteen Eighty-four</a></i>.</li>
<li>The <a href="/wiki/Toni_Morrison" title="Toni Morrison">Toni Morrison</a> novel <a href="/wiki/Song_of_Solomon_(novel)" title="Song of Solomon (novel)"><i>Song of Solomon</i></a> also uses the notion of a criminal syndicate of seven men, organized by the days of the week.</li>
<li>In <a href="/wiki/Agatha_Christie" title="Agatha Christie">Agatha Christie's</a> novel <a href="/wiki/The_Seven_Dials_Mystery" title="The Seven Dials Mystery">The Seven Dials Mystery</a>, the main character is a part of an organisation called the Seven Dials, which meets out of a pub called "The Seven Dials", and refers to its members by the numbers 1 to 7. This is likely to be a copy of the organisation in the Thursday Novel as there are Seven Dials and Seven Days.</li>
</ul>
